section#how-requests-work
  h2 How Requests Work
  aside
    p.tldr
      | Most of our Terms of Use explain your relationship with Dreambounty. This section is different — it explains the relationship between recipients and backers of Dreambounty requests, and who's responsible for what. This is what you're agreeing to when you create or back a Dreambounty request.
  br
  | Dreambounty provides a funding platform. When a user creates a request on Dreambounty, all users are invited to form a contract with the recipient of that request. Anyone who backs a request is accepting the request's contents, and forming that contract with the recipient.
  br
  br
  | Dreambounty is not a part of this contract — the contract is a direct legal agreement between recipients and their backers. Here are the terms that govern that agreement:
  br
  br
  | When a request is accepted by its recipient, the recipient must complete the request. Once a recipient has done so, they've satisfied their obligation to their backers.
  br
  br
  | Throughout the process, recipients owe their backers a high standard of effort, honest communication, and a dedication to bringing the request to life. At the same time, backers must understand that when they back a request, they're helping to create something new — not ordering something that already exists. There may be changes or delays, and there's a chance something could happen that prevents the recipient from being able to finish the request as promised.
  br
  br
  | If a recipient is unable to complete their request, they've failed to live up to the basic obligations of this agreement. To right this, they must make every reasonable effort to find another way of bringing the request to the best possible conclusion for backers. A recipient in this position has only remedied the situation and met their obligations to backers if:
  br
  br
  | • they post an update that explains what work has been done, how funds were used, and what prevents them from finishing the request as planned;
  br
  br
  | • they work diligently and in good faith to bring the request to the best possible conclusion in a timeframe that's communicated to backers;
  br
  br
  | • they're able to demonstrate that they've used funds appropriately and made every reasonable effort to complete the request as promised;
  br
  br
  | • they've been honest, and have made no material misrepresentations in their communication to backers; and
  br
  br
  | • they offer to return any remaining funds to backers who have not experienced the result of the request (in proportion to the amounts contributed), or else explain how those funds will be used to complete the request in some alternate form.
  br
  br
  | The recipient is solely responsible for fulfilling the promises made in their request. If they're unable to satisfy the terms of this agreement, they may be subject to legal action by backers.


section#how-funding-works
